\par \pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\fs24 =============
\par 
\par The moon and the moods of the land are linked. A green moon bespeaks fertility,
\par red violence. Look to the moon and nature will not catch you unawares.
\par However the moon is not such a simple being, to be read as a book... like
\par all intelligent beings it has much more complex moods. Often red and green
\par appear together, apparently conflicting colours blended with tranquil blues
\par and yellows.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s15\widctlpar\adjustright \cbpat1 \cgrid Well, although I am a reluctant supporter of coloured moons this is a cool explanation / idea for the role of such colour.
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\fs24 
\par 
\par The Fire Drakes - A group of orange stars seen in the southern night sky between
\par the months of Heat Uprising and Coruscating Shadows. Legend has it that they
\par are driven away by the winter months, during which time they hibernate in
\par caverns near the centre of the world, not bothering to take their nightly flight.
\par The cluster's formation changes slightly as they move, and between nights... in
\par an untraceable dance. This can be perceived only by the most dedicated observers.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright \cbpat1 {\fs24 Sounds cOoL.
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {\fs24 
\par 
\par Jewel
\par Light
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s15\widctlpar\adjustright \cbpat1 \cgrid The brightest star in the night sky and believed by some to be the origin of all life on Lu\rquote T
amohr. Whilst most find the idea of life originating from a star a little far fetched, the Jewel of Light star is well known, perhaps because it is the brightest.
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\fs24 
\par 
\par Sailor's Beacon - A bright star seen the year round which always traces a direct
\par line precisely NNW from its zenith. At nightfall, it marks roughly South... but
\par this is dependant on the season.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s15\widctlpar\adjustright \cbpat1 \cgrid cOoL.
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\fs24 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par Spark Shower - Usually about a month after the commet Fudamim is seen, a patch of
\par the night sky is filled with thousands of tiny lights. These are the souls of the
\par righteous, celebrating the just judgment passed by Fudamim. These lights glitter
\par in mostly white and blue, though there are traces of many other colours.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s15\widctlpar\adjustright \cbpat1 \cgrid Hmm, I am not sure I like the idea of this \ldblquote Fudamim\rdblquote . The religions on Lu\rquote Tam
ohr do not support immortal deities, except the thousand deity religion. Comets are surely an Island wide / Island watched event, so I do not believe people would commonly believe this comment to be a judgement of one of the thousand deities, as the follo
wing for this religion is quite small. I have no problem with the followers of the thousand deities beleiving it signifies Fudamims judgement etc of course. 
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\fs24 
\par 
\par Glittering Eyes - A pair of bright white stars that provide quite a large portion
\par of the night's illumination. Mothers oft say no nocturnal evil shall come to their
\par child, whilst the night is clear enough for the Glittering Eyes to watch over.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s15\widctlpar\adjustright \cbpat1 \cgrid cOoL
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\fs24 
\par 
