\par These stars are seen only in the winter months.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright \cbpat1 {\fs24 cOoL
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {\fs24 
\par Rozamelle Fires - A very loose cluster of predominantly dark red stars that tend
\par to flicker inconsistently. They are seen the year round.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright \cbpat1 {\fs24 cOoL
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {\fs24 
\par Fiory's Stair - A zigzag of bright white stars ending in an intricate pattern of
\par orange stars. Folklore speaks of a dragon that built a magical bridge to the other
\par side of the sky, The Fire Dragon. From its celestial roost it watches the night
\par for unwary travellers. These stars are seen all months except winter.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s15\widctlpar\adjustright \cbpat1 \cgrid This is a very cool description, the problem I see with it is this: If the star cluster is commonly known as Fiory\rquote 
s Stair, this would imply that the common man knows the name of the fire dragon Fiory. I could only see this being the case if a) Fiory is a common word for 
fire or something similar, and Fiory (the imm) was named for it, b) a lot more detail is known about dragons then I thought we wished to reveal. I\rquote 
m not sure how old Fiory is, but to have a star named after her in folklore would imply she is either a very old dragon, or has been seen / heard by makers of folklore in recent times. 
\par 
\par Having dragon-type superstitions in folklore I think is cool, but I think they should be general, rather than specific. Perhaps Fire Dragons stair is a better name? Or perhaps we wish to describe more detail here. Maybe Fiory 
infiltrated the highest circles of religion / folklore and told them what the legend of this st
ar formation is. Or maybe another dragon did for another reason, perhaps trying to get Fiory in trouble with the other dragons by having it seem as though her cover was blown to the mortals. A few possibilities here {\lang1024 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL
 74 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 12}{\fldrslt\f14\fs24}}}
